ROOT CAUSE: `program.cpp:7` indexes the five-element global array `x` with `n * 10000`. The debugger showed `x` has type `int [5]`, so valid indices are only `0..4`; on the first call `n == 0`, the computed index is `0`, but on the next call from `main` (`program.cpp:13`) `n == 1`, so the computed index is `10000`, and `&x[n * 10000]` points far past `&x[4]`. That out-of-bounds global-array read is what ASan reports as a global-buffer-overflow.

LOCAL FIX: Use an index that is within the bounds of `x`, and do not call `foo` for indices outside the array. For example, if `foo` is meant to print elements of `x`, change the code to:
```diff
 void foo(int n, float b) {
-  cout << "TEST " << x[n * 10000] << endl;
+  cout << "TEST " << x[n] << endl;
 }

 int main()
 {
-  for (auto i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
+  for (auto i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
     foo(i, 1.0);
   }
   return 0;
 }
```

GLOBAL FIX: Replace raw global-array indexing with a bounds-aware interface, such as `std::array<int, 5>` plus `.at()` or a helper that accepts a `std::span<const int>` and validates the index before access. This makes the array size part of the API/invariant instead of relying on callers and callees to manually keep loop bounds and index arithmetic consistent.

